SIMPLE: angina
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: angina
<hw>an*gi"na</hw> <pr>(⟦acr⟧n*j⟦imac⟧"n⟦adot⟧ <i>or</i>
⟦acr⟧n"j⟦icr⟧*n⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr.
<ets>angere</ets> to strangle, to choke. See <er>anger</er>, n.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any inflammatory affection of the
throat, as the quinsy, malignant sore throat, croup, etc., especially
such as tends to produce suffocation, choking, or shortness of
breath.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any spasmodic severe suffocative
pain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Angina pectoris.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Angina pectoris</b></col> <pr>(⟦acr⟧n*j⟦imac⟧"n⟦adot⟧
p⟦ecr⟧k"t⟦osl⟧*r⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <cd>Chest pain caused by myocardial
ischemia precipitated by exertion and relieved by rest. It is so called
because the pain is accompanied by a sense of suffocating contraction or
tightening of the lower part of the chest; -- called also
<altname>breast pang</altname>, <altname>spasm of the
chest</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><ent>anginal</ent>⟦br⟧
